					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">For RPG you would need a 16-bit (or even 32-bit) RNG with good uniform distribution (i.e. all the numbers has equal probability). It may be slower than simple RNGs.
<br />
<br />In any case, you need to find a compromise between pseudorandomness and possibility of manipulation. I.e. if you don't involve any randomization based on user's input, you only can have a pseudorandom sequence, which is always the same. Randomization based on user's input opens possibility of manipulation.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />My stuff at <a href="http://www.youtube.com/user/shiru8bit" class="postlink">YouTube</a>, <a href="http://soundcloud.com/shiru" class="postlink">SoundCloud</a></div>
